  "prompt": "How often do physics PhD students fail their qualifying exams?",
  "response": "The failure rates for qualifying exams in physics PhD programs can vary widely depending on the specific institution, the structure of the program, and the individual circumstances of the students. Generally, most physics PhD programs have a relatively high success rate for qualifying exams, with failure rates often reported to be between 10% to 30%, although this can vary.\n\nSome programs may allow students to retake the qualifying exams if they fail the first time, which can also influence the overall statistics. It's important to note that the qualifying exam is often designed to assess foundational knowledge and the ability to conduct research, and a variety of factors such as study habits, preparation, and personal situations can affect outcomes.\n\nIf you're looking for information specific to a particular program or institution, it's a good idea to consult that program's official statistics or speak with current students or faculty.",
